body:
I am using cocotb with verilator to simulate systemverilog code. Verilator is one of the most systemverilog supported open source simulator. But I got error when try to simulate nested systemverilog interface. 
I can not tell this is a bug, or feature request, so I just ask in the Q&A here. 

A simplified example below:
The .sv: There are 4 different ways I want to use the interface, only directly instantiate it at top level (test1) can be compiled and run successfully. If I want to access the sub-interface in the submodule, it report error. 
This code can be synthesis in vivado successfully even it does not really do anything. 
```
interface ift5(input clk);
    reg [31:0] cnt=0;
endinterface : ift5

interface ift4(input clk);
    ift5 tif5(.clk(clk));
endinterface : ift4

interface ift3(input clk);
    ift4 tif4(.clk(clk));
endinterface : ift3

interface ift2(input clk);
    ift3 tif3(.clk(clk));
endinterface : ift2

interface ift1(input clk);
    ift2 tif2(.clk(clk));
endinterface : ift1

module m1(ift1 tif1,input clk);
m3 m3(.tif3(tif1.tif2.tif3),.clk(clk));
endmodule:m1

module m2(ift2 tif2,input clk);
always @(posedge tif2.clk) begin
        tif2.tif3.tif4.tif5.cnt<=tif2.tif3.tif4.tif5.cnt+1'b1;
end
endmodule:m2

module m3(ift3 tif3,input clk);
always @(posedge tif3.clk) begin
        tif3.tif4.tif5.cnt<=tif3.tif4.tif5.cnt+1'b1;
end
endmodule:m3

module plsvsim(input clk
,output led
);
ift1 tif1(.clk(clk));
ift3 tif3(.clk(clk));
m3 m3(.tif3(tif3),.clk(clk));
m1 m1(.tif1(tif1),.clk(clk));
//m3 m3(.tif3(tif1.tif2.tif3),.clk(clk));
//m2 m2(.tif2(tif1.tif2),.clk(clk));
assign led=tif1.tif2.tif3.tif4.tif5.cnt[31];
endmodule


```
And the .py:
```
import cocotb
from cocotb.triggers import Timer, RisingEdge
from cocotb.clock import Clock
import numpy as np
import json



@cocotb.test()
async def plsvsim(dut):
    clock = Clock(dut.clk,10,units="ns")
    cocotb.start_soon(clock.start())
    for i in range(10):
        await RisingEdge(dut.clk)
```
When I run make for the cocotb, it call verilator and works for the test1. 
```
